--- !u!114 &987651012
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1272059702}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 5db7c314d17e1ef4cb9d0137b433360d, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::BookController
  pages:
  - "Chapter 1 \u2014 The Apartment\n\nThe city never truly went quiet. Even at 3
    a.m., the hum of distant traffic seeped through the walls of the small apartment
    like a tide that never fully pulled back.\n\nLena had lived here for two years,
    but tonight the familiar sounds felt different \u2014 as if the building itself
    was listening."
  - "She moved to the kitchen and opened the fridge out of habit, not hunger. The
    cold light fell across her face. Everything looked ordinary: leftovers, a half-empty
    bottle of water, a box of eggs.\n\nShe closed the door. The magnetic seal snapped
    shut with a sound she had never noticed before \u2014 sharp, definitive."
  - 'On the counter, the microwave''s digital clock pulsed: 03:17. She pressed the
    popcorn button without thinking. The carousel began to turn.


    Through the
    small window above the sink, the street lamp outside flickered once, twice, then
    held steady.'
  - "Chapter 2 \u2014 The Chair\n\nThe gaming chair by the desk had been her grandmother's
    idea of a practical gift. \"You sit too much anyway,\" the old woman had said,
    handing over the receipt. \"You might as well be comfortable.\"\n\nLena sat down.
    The seat accepted her weight slowly, like something giving permission."
  - "She pulled up the surveillance feed on her second monitor \u2014 four cameras,
    four corners of the building. In the top-right frame, the red indicator blinked
    steadily: on, off, on, off. A metronome counting seconds she couldn't get back.\n\nEverything
    was still. Nothing moved except the light."
  - "She turned back to the book on her desk \u2014 the one she had found in the
    fridge placement zone behind the old encyclopaedias. Its cover was blank. No
    title. No author.\n\nThe first page read only: 'You were meant to find this.'\n\nShe
    turned to page two."
  - "The remaining pages were filled with a single recurring sentence in slightly
    different handwriting each time, as if many people had copied it across many
    years:\n\n'Pay attention to what blinks in the dark.'\n\nLena set the book down
    carefully, face-down.\n\nIn the hallway, something knocked. Once. Then nothing.\n\n\u2014
    End \u2014"
